1. Spring Boot (Simplifying Spring) ‚ö°
üß† Logic:Spring Boot is an extension of the Spring Framework that aims to simplify the setup and configuration of Spring applications, especially for building $\mathbf{microservices}$ and $\mathbf{RESTful~APIs}$.Goal: Get Spring applications running with minimal configuration and setup time. It achieves this through:Auto-configuration: Automatically configures the application based on the dependencies (JARs) you add to your project (e.g., if you add the H2 database dependency, Spring Boot automatically configures the data source).Embedded Server: It includes an $\mathbf{embedded~Tomcat}$ (or Jetty/Undertow) server, so you don't need to deploy a WAR file to a separate application server.Starter Dependencies: Provides easy "starter" POM files (e.g., spring-boot-starter-web) that bundle common dependencies needed for a specific type of development.üìå Example:Javaimport org.springframework.boot.SpringApplication;
import org.springframework.boot.autoconfigure.SpringBootApplication;

// This single annotation enables auto-configuration, component scanning, etc.
@SpringBootApplication 
public class Application {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Launches the application, starts the embedded server
        SpringApplication.run(Application.class, args); 
    }
}
ü§π‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è Key Spring Boot Features:FeatureDescriptionBenefitStartersDependency bundles (e.g., web, data-jpa).Reduces build complexity.Embedded ServerTomcat/Jetty included and automatically configured.Simplifies deployment (JAR file deployment).ActuatorProvides production-ready features (metrics, health checks).Monitoring and management.@SpringBootApplicationCombines @Configuration, @EnableAutoConfiguration, and @ComponentScan.Single point of configuration.üßæ Notebook Points:Javaüìò Spring Boot:
‚Üí Extension of Spring to simplify setup and configuration
‚Üí Features: Auto-configuration, Embedded Server, Starter Dependencies

üî¢ Goal: Rapid application development and easy deployment
